Spritual \u2192 Spiritual", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aga_Khan_IV"}
{"title_page": "Joos Ulrich Heintz", "text_new": "\n\n'''Joos Ulrich Heintz''' (Born October 27th, 1945 in Zurich, Switzerland) is an Argentinean and Swiss mathematician. He is currently a professor [[emeritus]] at the [[University of Buenos Aires]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.uba.ar/archivos_uba/2014-09-10_968.pdf|title=Resolution University of Buenos Aires EXP-UBA 36.186/2014|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n== Biography ==\nAfter studying Mathematics and Cultural Anthropology at the [[University of Zurich|University of Z\u00fcrich]] to undergraduate level, he went on to receive a PhD in Mathematics in 1982 under the supervision of [[Volker Strassen]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.genealogy.math.ndsu.nodak.edu/id.php?id=44666|title=Joos Ulrich Heintz at the Mathematics Genealogy Project|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> He performed his [[habilitation]] in 1986 at the [[Goethe University Frankfurt|J.W.von Goethe University]] in Frankfurt am Main<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.uni-frankfurt.de/50699934/entwu_pc.pdf|title=W. Schwarz, J. Wolfart. Zur Geschichte des Mathematischen Seminars der Universt\u00e4t Frankfurt am Main von 1914 bis 1970 (2002)|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> where he also studied [[Turkology|Turcology]] and Sephardic history and culture. He was appointed [[Privatdozent]] at the J.W. Goethe Universit\u00e4t Frankfurt am Main. Until his retirement in 2017, he worked as a Full Professor at the University of Buenos Aires and [[University of Cantabria]]/Spain and as a Senior Researcher at the [[National Council for Scientific and Technological Development|National Council for Scientific and Technological Development (CONICET)]].\n\n== Research ==\nHeintz worked mainly in algebraic complexity theory, computational algebraic geometry, and semialgebraic geometry. For this purpose, he developed with his collaborators, different mathematical tools, e.g. the Bezout Inequality<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Heintz|first=Joos|date=1983|title=Definability and fast quantifier elimination in algebraically closed fields|url=|journal=Theoretical Computer Science|volume=24|issue=3|pages=239\u2013277|doi=10.1016/0304-3975(83)90002-6}}</ref> or the first effective [[Nullstellensatz]] in arbitrary characteristic<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Caniglia|first=L.|last2=Heintz|first2=J.|last3=Galligo|first3=A.|date=1988|title=Borne simple exponentielle pour les degr\u00e9s dans le th\u00e9or\u00e8me des z\u00e9ros sur un corps de caract\u00e9ristique quelconque|url=|journal=Comptes rendus de l'Acad\u00e9mie des Sciences|volume=307|pages=255\u2013258|via=}}</ref>. This allowed him and his collaborators to adapt Kronecker\u00b4s elimination theory<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kronecker|first=Leopold|date=1882|title=Grundz\u00fcge einer algebraischen Theorie der arithmetischen Gr\u00f6ssen|url=|journal=Journal f\u00fcr die reine und angewandte Mathematik|volume=92|pages=1\u2013122|via=}}</ref> to the complexity requirements of modern [[computer algebra]] and to prove that all reasonable geometric (not algebraic) computation problems are solvable in [[PSPACE]]. Later, he extended these complexity results to polynomial input systems given by arithmetic circuits. The final outcome was a worst case optimal probabilistic elimination algorithm with the ability to recognize \u201ceasily solvable\u201d input systems which was later implemented by Gr\u00e9goire Lecerf<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Giusti|first=M.|last2=Lecerf|first2=G.|last3=Salvy|first3=B.|date=2001|title=A Gr\u00f6bner free alternative for polynomial system solving|url=|journal=Journal of Complexity|volume=17|pages=154\u2013211|doi=10.1006/jcom.2000.0571}}</ref>. Finally, Heintz and his collaborators demonstrated that under very weak and natural assumptions, the worst case complexity of elimination algorithms is unavoidably exponential, independent of the chosen data structure<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Bank|first=B.|last2=Heintz|first2=Joos|last3=Matera|first3=G.|last4=Monta\u00f1a|first4=J.L.|last5=Pardo|first5=L.M.|last6=Rojas Paredes|first6=A.|date=2016|title=Quiz games as a model for information hiding|url=|journal=Journal of Complexity|volume=34|pages=1\u201329|doi=10.1016/j.jco.2015.11.005|arxiv=1508.07842}}</ref>. He applied his results and methods also to mixed integer optimization<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Bank|first=B.|last2=Heintz|first2=J.|last3=Krick|first3=T.|last4=Mandel|first4=R.|last5=Solern\u00f3|first5=P.|date=1993|title=Une borne optimale pour la programmation enti\u00e8re quasi-convexe|url=|journal=Bulletin de la Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 Math\u00e9matique de France|volume=121|issue=2|pages=299\u2013314|doi=10.24033/bsmf.2210}}</ref> and foundations of [[software engineering]]<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Heintz|first=J.|last2=Kuijpers|first2=B.|last3=Rojas Paredes|first3=A.|date=2013|title=Software Engineering and complexity in effective Algebraic Geometry|url=|journal=Journal of Complexity|volume=29|pages=92\u2013138|doi=10.1016/j.jco.2012.04.005}}</ref>.\n\nFurthermore, in the field of linguistics, he identified the [[morphology]] and [[phonology]] of the Turkish languages as a regular language.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Heintz|first=J.|last2=Sch\u00f6nig|first2=C.|date=1991|title=Turkic morphology as regular language|url=http://www.orientalstudies.ru/eng/images/pdf/a_pang_1991.pdf|journal=Central Asiatic Journal|volume=35|pages=96\u2013122|via=}}</ref>\n\nIn 1987, Heintz founded the Argentinean research group [[Noa\u00ef Fitchas]] in Buenos Aires. This group was transformed into the international working group [[TERA (Turbo Evaluation and Rapid Algorithms)]] with collaborators from several Argentinean, French, Spanish and German universities and research institutions, such as the University of Buenos Aires, CONICET, University of Nizza, \u00c9cole Polytechnique at Paris, Universidad de Cantabria (Spain), and Humboldt University at Berlin. Noa\u00ef Fitchas was used as a pseudonym for the Argentinean group and numerous influential papers in Computer Algebra were published in the nineties under this name<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Berenstein|first=C.A.|last2=Struppa|first2=D.C.|date=1991|title=Recent improvements in the complexity of the effective Nullstellensatz|url=|journal=Linear Algebra and Its Applications|volume=157|pages=203\u2013215|doi=10.1016/0024-3795(91)90115-D}}</ref>\n\nHeintz was a member of the editorial boards of several international journals, including the Foundations of Computational Mathematics, Computational Complexity and Applicable Algebra in Engineering, and Communication and Computing, from which he received three best paper awards.\n\nIn 2003, Heintz was awarded the Argentinean [[Konex Award|Konex Medal of Merit]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fundacionkonex.org/b2570-joos-yunus-heintz|title=Premio Konex 2003: Ingenier\u00eda Electr\u00f3nica, Comunicaci\u00f3n e Inform\u00e1tica|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n== Important publications ==\n* Heintz, Joos (1983). Definability and fast quantifier elimination in algebraically closed fields. [[Theoretical Computer Science (journal)|Theoretical Computer Science]]. 24. pp. 239-277. https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-3975(83)90002-6\n* Caniglia L., Galligo A., Heintz J. (1989) Some new effectivity bounds in computational geometry. In: Mora T. (eds) Applied Algebra, Algebraic Algorithms and Error-Correcting Codes. AAECC 1988. [[Lecture Notes in Computer Science]], vol 357. Springer, Berlin, Heidelberg Best Paper Award. https://doi.org/10.1007/3-540-51083-4_54\n* Bank B, Giusti M., Heintz J.,  Mbakop G.M. (1997). Polar varieties, real equation solving, and data structures: the hypersurface case. Journal of Complexity 13 (1). pp. 5-27 https://doi.org/10.1006/jcom.1997.0432 1997 Journal of Complexity Best Paper Award\n* Giusti M., Heintz J., Morais J.E., Morgenstern J., Pardo L.M. (1998). Straight-line programs in geometric elimination theory. [[Journal of Pure and Applied Algebra]] 124 (1-3) (1998) 101-146 https://doi.org/10.1016/S0022-4049(96)00099-0\n* Heintz J., Kuijpers B., Rojas Paredes A. (2013). Software Engineering and complexity in effective Algebraic Geometry. Journal of Complexity 29 (1). pp. 92-138 https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jco.2012.04.005 2013 Journal of Complexity Best Paper Award\n* Bank B., Giusti M., Heintz J., Lecerf G., Matera G., Solern\u00f3 G. (2015). Degeneracy Loci and Polynomial Equation Solving. [[Foundations of Computational Mathematics]],15 (1). pp. 159-184 https://doi.org/10.1007/s10208-014-9214-z<!-- References -->\n\n<br />\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://dblp.uni-trier.de/pers/h/Heintz:Joos.html Joos Heintz at Computer Science Bibliography Server]\n\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "text_old": "{{Copy edit|for=grammar, style, and usage|date=March 2020}}\n\n'''Joos Ulrich Heintz''' (Born October 27th, 1945 in Zurich, Switzerland) is an Argentinean and Swiss mathematician. He is currently a professor [[emeritus]] at the [[University of Buenos Aires]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.uba.ar/archivos_uba/2014-09-10_968.pdf|title=Resolution University of Buenos Aires EXP-UBA 36.186/2014|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n== Biography ==\nAfter studying Mathematics and Cultural Anthropology at the [[University of Zurich|University of Z\u00fcrich]] to undergraduate level, he went on to receive a PhD in Mathematics in 1982 under the supervision of [[Volker Strassen]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.genealogy.math.ndsu.nodak.edu/id.php?id=44666|title=Joos Ulrich Heintz at the Mathematics Genealogy Project|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> He performed his [[habilitation]] in 1986 at the [[Goethe University Frankfurt|J.W.von Goethe University]] in Frankfurt am Main<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.uni-frankfurt.de/50699934/entwu_pc.pdf|title=W. Schwarz, J. Wolfart. Zur Geschichte des Mathematischen Seminars der Universt\u00e4t Frankfurt am Main von 1914 bis 1970 (2002)|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> where he also studied [[Turkology|Turcology]] and Sephardic history and culture. He was appointed [[Privatdozent]] at the J.W. Goethe Universit\u00e4t Frankfurt am Main. Until his retirement in 2017, he worked as a Full Professor at the University of Buenos Aires and [[University of Cantabria]]/Spain and as a Senior Researcher at the [[National Council for Scientific and Technological Development|National Council for Scientific and Technological Development (CONICET)]].\n\n== Research ==\nHeintz worked mainly in algebraic complexity theory, computational algebraic geometry, and semialgebraic geometry. For this purpose, he developed with his collaborators, different mathematical tools, e.g. the Bezout Inequality<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Heintz|first=Joos|date=1983|title=Definability and fast quantifier elimination in algebraically closed fields|url=|journal=Theoretical Computer Science|volume=24|issue=3|pages=239\u2013277|doi=10.1016/0304-3975(83)90002-6}}</ref> or the first effective [[Nullstellensatz]] in arbitrary characteristic<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Caniglia|first=L.|last2=Heintz|first2=J.|last3=Galligo|first3=A.|date=1988|title=Borne simple exponentielle pour les degr\u00e9s dans le th\u00e9or\u00e8me des z\u00e9ros sur un corps de caract\u00e9ristique quelconque|url=|journal=Comptes rendus de l'Acad\u00e9mie des Sciences|volume=307|pages=255\u2013258|via=}}</ref>. This allowed him and his collaborators to adapt Kronecker\u00b4s elimination theory<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kronecker|first=Leopold|date=1882|title=Grundz\u00fcge einer algebraischen Theorie der arithmetischen Gr\u00f6ssen|url=|journal=Journal f\u00fcr die reine und angewandte Mathematik|volume=92|pages=1\u2013122|via=}}</ref> to the complexity requirements of modern [[computer algebra]] and to prove that all reasonable geometric (not algebraic) computation problems are solvable in [[PSPACE]]. Later, he extended these complexity results to polynomial input systems given by arithmetic circuits. The final outcome was a worst case optimal probabilistic elimination algorithm with the ability to recognize \u201ceasily solvable\u201d input systems which was later implemented by Gr\u00e9goire Lecerf<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Giusti|first=M.|last2=Lecerf|first2=G.|last3=Salvy|first3=B.|date=2001|title=A Gr\u00f6bner free alternative for polynomial system solving|url=|journal=Journal of Complexity|volume=17|pages=154\u2013211|doi=10.1006/jcom.2000.0571}}</ref>. Finally, Heintz and his collaborators demonstrated that under very weak and natural assumptions, the worst case complexity of elimination algorithms is unavoidably exponential, independent of the chosen data structure<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Bank|first=B.|last2=Heintz|first2=Joos|last3=Matera|first3=G.|last4=Monta\u00f1a|first4=J.L.|last5=Pardo|first5=L.M.|last6=Rojas Paredes|first6=A.|date=2016|title=Quiz games as a model for information hiding|url=|journal=Journal of Complexity|volume=34|pages=1\u201329|doi=10.1016/j.jco.2015.11.005|arxiv=1508.07842}}</ref>. He applied his results and methods also to mixed integer optimization<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Bank|first=B.|last2=Heintz|first2=J.|last3=Krick|first3=T.|last4=Mandel|first4=R.|last5=Solern\u00f3|first5=P.|date=1993|title=Une borne optimale pour la programmation enti\u00e8re quasi-convexe|url=|journal=Bulletin de la Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 Math\u00e9matique de France|volume=121|issue=2|pages=299\u2013314|doi=10.24033/bsmf.2210}}</ref> and foundations of [[software engineering]]<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Heintz|first=J.|last2=Kuijpers|first2=B.|last3=Rojas Paredes|first3=A.|date=2013|title=Software Engineering and complexity in effective Algebraic Geometry|url=|journal=Journal of Complexity|volume=29|pages=92\u2013138|doi=10.1016/j.jco.2012.04.005}}</ref>.\n\nFurthermore, in the field of linguistics, he identified the [[morphology]] and [[phonology]] of the Turkish languages as a regular language.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Heintz|first=J.|last2=Sch\u00f6nig|first2=C.|date=1991|title=Turkic morphology as regular language|url=http://www.orientalstudies.ru/eng/images/pdf/a_pang_1991.pdf|journal=Central Asiatic Journal|volume=35|pages=96\u2013122|via=}}</ref>\n\nIn 1987, Heintz founded the Argentinean research group [[Noa\u00ef Fitchas]] in Buenos Aires. This group was transformed into the international working group [[TERA (Turbo Evaluation and Rapid Algorithms)]] with collaborators from several Argentinean, French, Spanish and German universities and research institutions, such as the University of Buenos Aires, CONICET, University of Nizza, \u00c9cole Polytechnique at Paris, Universidad de Cantabria (Spain), and Humboldt University at Berlin. Noa\u00ef Fitchas was used as a pseudonym for the Argentinean group and numerous influential papers in Computer Algebra were published in the nineties under this name<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Berenstein|first=C.A.|last2=Struppa|first2=D.C.|date=1991|title=Recent improvements in the complexity of the effective Nullstellensatz|url=|journal=Linear Algebra and Its Applications|volume=157|pages=203\u2013215|doi=10.1016/0024-3795(91)90115-D}}</ref>\n\nHeintz was a member of the editorial boards of several international journals, including the Foundations of Computational Mathematics, Computational Complexity and Applicable Algebra in Engineering, and Communication and Computing, from which he received three best paper awards.\n\nIn 2003, Heintz was awarded the Argentinean [[Konex Award|Konex Medal of Merit]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fundacionkonex.org/b2570-joos-yunus-heintz|title=Premio Konex 2003: Ingenier\u00eda Electr\u00f3nica, Comunicaci\u00f3n e Inform\u00e1tica|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n== Important publications ==\n* Heintz, Joos (1983). Definability and fast quantifier elimination in algebraically closed fields. [[Theoretical Computer Science (journal)|Theoretical Computer Science]]. 24. pp. 239-277. https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-3975(83)90002-6\n* Caniglia L., Galligo A., Heintz J. (1989) Some new effectivity bounds in computational geometry. In: Mora T. (eds) Applied Algebra, Algebraic Algorithms and Error-Correcting Codes. AAECC 1988. [[Lecture Notes in Computer Science]], vol 357. Springer, Berlin, Heidelberg Best Paper Award. https://doi.org/10.1007/3-540-51083-4_54\n* Bank B, Giusti M., Heintz J.,  Mbakop G.M. (1997). Polar varieties, real equation solving, and data structures: the hypersurface case. Journal of Complexity 13 (1). pp. 5-27 https://doi.org/10.1006/jcom.1997.0432 1997 Journal of Complexity Best Paper Award\n* Giusti M., Heintz J., Morais J.E., Morgenstern J., Pardo L.M. (1998). Straight-line programs in geometric elimination theory. [[Journal of Pure and Applied Algebra]] 124 (1-3) (1998) 101-146 https://doi.org/10.1016/S0022-4049(96)00099-0\n* Heintz J., Kuijpers B., Rojas Paredes A. (2013). Software Engineering and complexity in effective Algebraic Geometry. Journal of Complexity 29 (1). pp. 92-138 https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jco.2012.04.005 2013 Journal of Complexity Best Paper Award\n* Bank B., Giusti M., Heintz J., Lecerf G., Matera G., Solern\u00f3 G. (2015). Degeneracy Loci and Polynomial Equation Solving. [[Foundations of Computational Mathematics]],15 (1). pp. 159-184 https://doi.org/10.1007/s10208-014-9214-z<!-- References -->\n\n<br />\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://dblp.uni-trier.de/pers/h/Heintz:Joos.html Joos Heintz at Computer Science Bibliography Server]\n\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "name_user": "Wafflyjar", "label": "safe", "comment": "Removed maintenance notice", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Joos_Ulrich_Heintz"}
{"title_page": "Fort Nuestra Senora de la Soledad", "text_new": "{{Infobox NRHP\n  | name = Fort Nuestra Se\u00f1ora de la Soledad\n  | nrhp_type = \n  | image = Fort Nuestra Se\u00f1ora de la Soled\u00e5d - Umatac, Guam - DSC00948.JPG\n  | caption = \n  | nearest_city= [[Umatac, Guam]]\n  | coordinates = {{coord|13|17|36|N|144|39|27|E|display=inline,title}}\n| locmapin = Guam\n| map_label =Fort Nuestra Se\u00f1ora de la Soledad\n  | built = c.1802-1819\n  | builder = \n  | architecture = \n  | added = October 18, 1974\n  | area = {{convert|8|acre}}\n  | governing_body = State   \n  | refnum = 74002042<ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|version=2010a}}</ref>\n}} \n'''Fort Nuestra Se\u00f1ora de la Soledad''' ([[Spanish language|Spanish]]:''Fuerte de Nuestra Se\u00f1ora de la Soledad'') is a fortification near [[Umatac, Guam|Umatac]], [[Guam]]. Built by the Spanish probably between 1802 and 1819, it was the fourth of four fortifications that protected an anchorage for [[Manila galleon|galleon]]s transiting between Acapulco, Mexico and the Philippines, a route that fell out of use in 1815 with Mexican independence.\n\n[[File:Cannons - Fort Nuestra Se\u00f1ora de la Soled\u00e5d - Umatac, Guam - DSC00958.JPG|left|150px]]\nThe fort has been damaged by treasure-hunters;  it was made into a park following World War II.  It was listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]] in 1974.<ref name=nris/><ref name=nrhpdoc>{{cite web|url={{NRHP url|id=74002042}} |title=National Register of Historic Places Inventory/Nomination: Fort Nuestra Se\u00f1ora de la Soledad |author=David T. Lotz |date=January 8, 1974 |publisher=National Park Service}} and {{NRHP url|id=74002042|title=accompanying photos|photos=y}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Commons category-inline|Fort Nuestra Se\u00f1ora de la Soled\u00e5d}}\n\n{{National Register of Historic Places}}\n\n[[Category:Infrastructure completed in 1819]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures on the National Register of Historic Places in Guam]]\n[[Category:Fortifications of the Spanish East Indies]]\n[[Category:1800s establishments in the Spanish East Indies]]\n\n{{Guam-NRHP-stub}}\n{{Guam-struct-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox NRHP\n  | name = Fort Nuestra Senora de la Soledad\n  | nrhp_type = \n  | image = Fort Nuestra Se\u00f1ora de la Soled\u00e5d - Umatac, Guam - DSC00948.JPG\n  | caption = \n  | nearest_city= [[Umatac, Guam]]\n  | coordinates = {{coord|13|17|36|N|144|39|27|E|display=inline,title}}\n| locmapin = Guam\n| map_label =Fort Nuestra Senora de la Soledad\n  | built = c.1802-1819\n  | builder = \n  | architecture = \n  | added = October 18, 1974\n  | area = {{convert|8|acre}}\n  | governing_body = State   \n  | refnum = 74002042<ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|version=2010a}}</ref>\n}} \n'''Fort Nuestra Senora de la Soledad''' ([[Spanish language|Spanish]]:''Fuerte de Nuestra Se\u00f1ora de la Soledad'') is a fortification near [[Umatac, Guam|Umatac]], [[Guam]]. Built by the Spanish probably between 1802 and 1819, it was the fourth of four fortifications that protected an anchorage for [[Manila galleon|galleon]]s transiting between Acapulco, Mexico and the Philippines, a route that fell out of use in 1815 with Mexican independence.\n\n[[File:Cannons - Fort Nuestra Se\u00f1ora de la Soled\u00e5d - Umatac, Guam - DSC00958.JPG|left|150px]]\nThe fort has been damaged by treasure-hunters;  it was made into a park following World War II.  It was listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]] in 1974.<ref name=nris/><ref name=nrhpdoc>{{cite web|url={{NRHP url|id=74002042}} |title=National Register of Historic Places Inventory/Nomination: Fort Nuestra Senora de la Soledad |author=David T. Lotz |date=January 8, 1974 |publisher=National Park Service}} and {{NRHP url|id=74002042|title=accompanying photos|photos=y}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Commons category-inline|Fort Nuestra Se\u00f1ora de la Soled\u00e5d}}\n\n{{National 